{"questionId":"27958","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following diagram shows a park bounded by a fence in the shape of a quadrilateral <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ABCD</mtext></math>. A straight path crosses through the park from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math> to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>D</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AB</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>85</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>AD</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>85</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>BC</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mover><mtext>B</mtext><mo>^</mo></mover><mtext>D</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>°</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mover><mtext>C</mtext><mo>^</mo></mover><mtext>D</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>120</mn><mo>°</mo></math></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/cf5c1f3d8dceb95dbd0d989858e69331e40cc87e.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The size of angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext><mover><mtext>A</mtext><mo>^</mo></mover><mtext>D</mtext></math> rounds to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>77</mn><mo>°</mo></math>, correct to the nearest degree. Use <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext><mover><mtext>A</mtext><mo>^</mo></mover><mtext>D</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>77</mn><mo>°</mo></math>&nbsp;for the rest of this question.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A landscaping firm proposes a new design for the park. Fences <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BC</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>CD</mtext></math> are to be&nbsp;replaced by a fence in the shape of a circular arc <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BED</mtext></math> with center <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math>. This is illustrated&nbsp;in the following diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/ca42cfd755882be1339a63339fd674e96b0ef82b.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the area of the shaded region in the proposed park.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>77</mn><mn>360</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>×</mo><msup><mfenced><mn>85</mn></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>3519</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>91</mn><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>M1</strong> </em>for correctly substituted area of sector formula, <em><strong>M1</strong> </em>for subtraction of their area from part (c).</p>\n<p><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1330</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mtext>m</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1334</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>93</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27958","referenceCode":"22N.2.SL.TZ0.2f","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the area of the shaded region in the proposed park.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"f","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.4—The circle, arc and area of sector, degrees only"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}